The true Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that corresponds to the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses out of Egypt.
I grew up with this.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and their three Red Armies were driven out of their strongholds in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Persecuted and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and impassable grazing land, with Mao leading the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against incredibly bad prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers had remained – exhausted, badly battered, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
In what extent does China's founding myth correspond to reality?
It was 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, that I embarked on a search for its traces.
It is still a daunting journey through areas that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I found 40 of them and conducted conversations with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or managed to make it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, barely taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: They had taken his father captive and wouldn't let him go until Huang agreed.
He thought about desertion, but remained, fearing he'd be caught and shot.
Many fled.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the battle at the Xiang River, the first major battle of the army on the march.
However, at most 15,000 died in the battle, the others disappeared.
Another battle, which takes place at the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Apparently, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of the nationalist troops that were guarding the chains of the Luding Bridge with machine guns and made the way clear for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that the crossing of the Dadu was the most significant event on the Long March in its entirety, and it is thus celebrated today.
But documents that I have accessed suggest that the general who led the division over the Dadu initially told party historians a completely different story. "The thing wasn't as complicated as people made it out to be later on," he said. "When you investigate historical facts, you should respect the truth.
How it's presented is another matter."
So the legend continues.
Over the Dadu there was only a skirmish.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The participants on the march did not know where they were heading.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they came together in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could hardly feed its own population, not to mention the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
The women were ordered to turn back and return home because there wasn't enough food.
Just a month after the three Red Armies were united, the party decided that the Long March had to continue.
However, it was saved by Chiang Kai-shek's kidnapping by a general he had appointed to destroy the communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
However, not for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and were tasked with seeking help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
But Mao gave them contradictory orders, so they neither fought nor retreated.
Encircled in poor land, where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Yet it is missing in official historiography.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to turn her into a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny the years she had dedicated to the army for decades.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despaired and held on.
The hunger led the soldiers to take hostages to extort ransom.
The liquidations continued until practically no more officers were left to take command in the battles.
If the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They took their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other nations.

Was trieb sie dazu an?
Ich befragte einen der obersten Generäle, was er damals über den Kommunismus wusste. „Ich hatte damals wie heute keine Ahnung“, antwortete er. „Ich bezweifele sogar, dass Mao selbst überhaupt wusste, was das war.“ Für ihn, der äußerste Armut und Unterdrückung überlebt hatte, war der Kommunismus ein schöner Traum, der ihn am Leben hielt, die Hoffnung auf eine gerechte und fortschrittliche Gesellschaft.
Niemand wusste vielleicht – oder konnte wissen –, wie viel Leid noch bevorstand, wie groß das Opfer und wie enorm der Unterschied zwischen Traum und Wirklichkeit sein würde.
